#1 Recently-diagnosed adenocarcinoma of the descending colon
This diagnosis is based on a colonoscopy performed at an outside hospital with the pathology slides being read here.  The colonoscopy report that Mr. Savage brings with him is not extremely detailed, and the pathology from the biopsy during the EGD is not clear of whether this is from the cardia or from above the GE junction.  After discussion with Dr. Ostrander, we thought it would be prudent for the colonoscopy and EGD to be repeated.  The colonoscopy will provide us with details of the exact location and size of polyps and masses, and repeat biopsies can be performed.  A repeat EGD can be done to confirm the presence or absence of Barrett's esophagus.
Mr. Savage has had a number of tests performed here at Gothenburg Dental Hospital which includes a CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis which demonstrates a circumferential wall thickening of the distal sigmoid colon which should represent the recently discovered colon carcinoma.  There was no CT evidence of metastatic disease.  A chest x-ray was performed on the 20th of July which demonstrated borderline cardiomegaly, and the chest was otherwise negative.
Mr. Savage is currently on Warfarin therapy, and our plan is for him to come off his Warfarin, for him to have his colonoscopy and EGD with biopsies and then to be seen by a colorectal surgeon the next day after remaining on clear liquids after his procedures and then to have surgery planned for the following day and therefore he will remain with a suitable INR during that period.
#2 Preoperative assessment
This is currently being completed by Dr. Olson from Wisconsin, and a PET myocardial perfusion scan is being performed, which does show an ejection fraction of 33% with a large fixed defect consistent with infarction involving apical, anterior, and anteroseptal segments and severe left ventricular enlargement.  Also, he was found to be in atrial fibrillation with a rapid ventricular response on an ECG on the 20th of July, and subsequently his rate-controlling medications have been adjusted.
Overnight oximetry was performed on the 20th of July 2010, and demonstrates 127 drops in saturation of at least 4% with a very abnormal baseline suggestive of obstructive sleep apnea.  It was felt that Mr. Savage should be evaluated in Saint Catherine Health Center for the possibility of an overnight sleep study and prior to any surgery.
Once these tests and consults have been completed, we will see Mr. Savage at the time of his consult with the colorectal surgeon.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

